Once fired Lake City brass fully processed and ready to reload. We go the extra mile to ensure that you are receiving the highest quality brass available for reloading. It is fully safe to shoot these cases and if you wish, can be removed with normal household solvents.

title: For Sale:  Canik TP9SA --- New, Less than 100 rounds fired
postcontent: So there is a story to this gun. I believe in being fully upfront with everything I know about a product I'm selling. The gun for sale is the second TP9SA I have owned. The first one went back home to Century Arms twice. The first time was for stove pipes, failure to feed, failure to eject. I sent it back, where the springs were replaced, things were poked on and "fixed", and had it back in a few weeks’ time.   Hoping it was now all I had read this gun could be, I eagerly took it out to the range. It was now an ejecting son-of-a-gun! The problem now was that it was ejecting straight into my forehead. Ever had a hot 9mm casing get lodged between your glasses and your skin? Not fun.   So back it went again. This time, I got an entirely new gun out of the deal. Took it out yesterday, and got about what I expected. Overall, its better. It jams maybe once every 10-20 shots on average, and more or less ejects to the side, although it will throw a few at your head. Yes I know you’re supposed to put at least 400 rounds through it before it settles in, but I’m just done with it. I've had enough, and I’m looking to move to something else, hence the low price.  Aside from the gun, I’ll throw in the last 50 or so 9mm rounds I have left. Are you a gunsmith? Know a good one? Feel like dealing with Canik? This may be the right gun at the right price for you. The original warranty is not transferable, but I haven’t registered this gun with them yet; you may be able to.   Please reach out with any questions, and thanks for looking.

title: For Sale:  Zev Technologies Custom Glock 34
postcontent:
Zev Technologies Custom Glock 34
Custom G34 (9mm) with the Dragonfly slide.  I have replaced the Zev barrel with a Storm Lake 6” ported barrel (six ports).  I decided to leave in the Glock OEM trigger components for reliability. There is stippling along the frame where needed and it is not overly aggressive.  Honestly, it is just right.  The slide is also pre-milled for a Trijicon RMR micro red dot sight.  Sights are Zev’s own with blacked out rear, pushed all the way to the rear of the slide and a front red fiber optic.  Both front and rear sights have serrations to break up any glare.
Pistol is used but certainly not abused with about 500 rounds through it…just lots of dry firing and draws from the holster.  Finish on the slide is impeccable and there is no wear on the frame.  Comes with one OEM 17 round magazine.
This pistol is highly customized and ready for 2 and 3-gun matches (or just about anything else for that matter) as is, though there are plenty of other changes one could make.  It’s nice to have options.  Pistol with upgrades costs on the order of $2000 and they sell new for this price all day, every day (see here: https://www.omahaoutdoors.com/zev-g34-g3-17-gun-dfly-dlc).

title: For Sale:  World war 2 Japanese Type 2 Rifle
postcontent: For your consideration is this Japanese type 2 Paratrooper Rifle. The primary difference between this rifle and the Type 99 was the fact that it had a bolt that locked the two pieces into place rather than being made of a single piece. The purpose for this was to allow the Japanese paratroopers to carry them in a bag while they jumped and then piece it together on the ground. There were only 24000 of these types of rifles made throughout the duration of the war. Compare this to the millions of K98s, M1 Garands, Nagants, and even T99s and you can understand why it’s a unique bird. The rifle still has a full imperial Chrysanthemum as well as it’s original anti aircraft sites. Both halves Match however the bolt is ~50 numbers off from the remainder of the rifle. This is commonly seen on rifles brought back from the Pacific Campaigns as it was common procedures to confiscate the bolt while in transit back to the states. Once back they often just grabbed a random bolt assembly from a large group of readily available ones. This rifle displays well and will be a great addition to any advanced World War 2 firearm collection. I can send additional detailed pictures upon request. Will consider trades for an original WW2 era German Luger or other WW2 era firearms
